  • Field Details

    • m_tupDescHolder

      TupleDescriptor.Interned[] m_tupDescHolder
      Associated tuple descriptor, redundantly kept accessible here as well as opaquely bound into a SwitchPointCache method handle.

      This one-element array containing the descriptor is what gets bound into the handle, so the descriptor can be freed for GC at invalidation time (rather than waiting for the next tuple-descriptor request to replace the handle). Only accessed from SwitchPointCache computation methods or TupleDescImpl factory methods, all of which execute on the PG thread; no synchronization fuss needed.

      When null, no computation method has run (or none since invalidation), and the state is not known. Otherwise, the single element is the result to be returned by the tupleDescriptor() API method.

    • cacheId

      int cacheId()
      Description copied from class: CatalogObjectImpl.Addressed
      Returns the ID of a syscache that is searchable with a single oid key to retrieve the cacheTuple defining this instance of this class.

      This implementation throws UnsupportedOperationException and must be overridden in every subclass, unless a subclass supplies its own computation method for cacheTuple that does not use this.

      Overrides:
      cacheId in class CatalogObjectImpl.Addressed<RegClass>

    • invalidate

      void invalidate(List<SwitchPointCache.SwitchPoint> sps, List<Runnable> postOps)
      Called from Factory's invalidateRelation to set up the invalidation of this relation's metadata.

      Adds this relation's SwitchPoint to the caller's list so that, if more than one is to be invalidated, that can be done in bulk. Adds to postOps any operations the caller should conclude with after invalidating the SwitchPoint.

      Overrides:
      invalidate in class CatalogObjectImpl.Addressed<RegClass>

    • dualHandshake

      void dualHandshake(RegType dual)
      Called by the corresponding RegType instance if it has just looked us up.

      Because the SwitchPointCache recomputation methods always execute on the PG thread, plain access to an instance field suffices here.
